      "description": "# â™»ï¸  The Terraform development cycle\n\n It's time to start running Terraform commands in the terminal below! You may find it helpful to resize the terminal in the Codespaces interface when you want to read long outputs. \n\n The following steps will walk you through the main Terraform commands: \n\n - `terraform init`: This retrieves providers and creates a state file. You only have to run it if you changed the providers. Running `terraform init` is like building a race track -- essential at the start of your project, but not something you'll do every day! \n - `terraform plan`: This asks Terraform whta will have to change to make the infrastructure look like your code. It uses API calls to read the current state of your Okta organization. `terraform plan` will print a report to your terminal that says what will have to change, but it won't make those changes. \n - `terraform apply`: This tells Terraform to go make your Okta tenant match your Terraform code! This might create or destroy resources if necessary. `terraform apply` has lots of options that we won't use today, but you can see them by running the command `terraform apply --help`"
